In October 2022, Musk announced on Twitter the start of production of the {{convert|500|mile|km|abbr=out|adj=on}} range model that would be delivered in December.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2022/10/07/business/tesla-semi-truck-production/index.html |title=Tesla set to deliver long-delayed electric trucks to Pepsi in December |date=October 7, 2022 |website=CNN Business |last=McFarland |first=Matt |access-date=October 10, 2022  |archive-date=November 2, 2022  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20221102120652/https://www.cnn.com/2022/10/07/business/tesla-semi-truck-production/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref> In November 2022, the company reported that a Tesla Semi had completed a {{convert|500|mile|km|abbr=out|adj=on}} drive while weighing {{Convert|81000|lb|kg}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.drive.com.au/news/tesla-semi-reportedly-completes-800km-range-test-us-deliveries-to-begin-within-days/ |website=Drive |title=Tesla Semi reportedly completes 800km range test, US deliveries to begin within days |first1=Jordan |last1=Mulach |date=November 29, 2022 |access-date=November 29, 2022 |archive-date=November 29, 2022  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20221129202055/https://www.drive.com.au/news/tesla-semi-reportedly-completes-800km-range-test-us-deliveries-to-begin-within-days/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last1=Sriram |first1=Akash |date=December 2, 2022 |title=Musk delivers first Tesla truck, but no update on output, pricing |language=en |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/autos-transportation/musk-delivers-first-tesla-semi-trucks-2022-12-02/ |access-date=December 2, 2022}}</ref> 

On December 1, 2022, Tesla began customer deliveries at an evening event hosted at the manufacturing facility in Nevada. [[PepsiCo]] received the first Semis of their large order for use with [[Pepsi]] beverage and [[Frito-Lay]] snack food transportation fleets.<ref name=engadget20221202>{{cite news |url=https://www.engadget.com/tesla-finally-delivers-its-first-production-semi-to-pepsi-014214184.html |title=Tesla finally delivers its first production Semi |first1=A. |last1=Tarantola |work=Engadget |date=December 1, 2022 |access-date=December 2, 2022 |archive-date=January 31, 2023  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20230131081212/https://www.engadget.com/tesla-finally-delivers-its-first-production-semi-to-pepsi-014214184.html |url-status=live }}</ref> PepsiCo Vice President Mike O'Connell stated that the Semis can haul Frito-Lay food products for around 425 miles (684&nbsp;km), but for heavier loads of sodas, the trucks will make shorter trips of around 100 miles (160&nbsp;km).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2022/12/16/pepsico-is-using-36-tesla-semis-in-its-fleet-and-is-upgrading-facilities-for-more-in-2023-exec-says.html |title=PepsiCo is using 36 Tesla Semis in its fleet and is upgrading facilities for more in 2023, exec says |work=CNBC |location=US |date=December 16, 2022 |access-date=December 30, 2022 |archive-date=April 4, 2023  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20230404084223/https://www.cnbc.com/2022/12/16/pepsico-is-using-36-tesla-semis-in-its-fleet-and-is-upgrading-facilities-for-more-in-2023-exec-says.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

In late 2023, Tesla announced plans to establish a charging network for the Semi in the southwestern US. The network is expected to cost around $100M.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.greencarreports.com/news/1140373_report-tesla-seeks-100m-from-us-for-semi-charging-route | title=Report: Tesla seeks $100M from US for Semi charging route | date=August 2, 2023 | access-date=October 18, 2023  | archive-date=November 2, 2023  | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20231102005922/https://www.greencarreports.com/news/1140373_report-tesla-seeks-100m-from-us-for-semi-charging-route | url-status=live }}</ref>

Following years of delays, Tesla used ACT Expo 2024 to provide updated production and deployment plans for the Tesla Semi program including plans for volume Semi production beginning in 2026 and outlined additional deployments for [[PepsiCo|PepsiCo’s]] fleet.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Ohnsman |first=Alan |title=Elon Musk Said Tesla’s Semi Would Transform Trucking. 6 Years Later, Customers Are Still Waiting |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alanohnsman/2023/05/10/elon-musk-said-teslas-semi-would-transform-trucking-6-years-later-customers-are-still-waiting/ |access-date=2026-06-02 |website=Forbes |language=en}}</ref>

As of May 2024, [[Walmart]], [[Costco]], [[Sysco]], [[Martin-Brower|Martin Brower]], and [[US Foods]] were also testing the Semi.<ref>{{cite news |date=May 9, 2024 |title=Tesla's Power Play: Costco, Sysco, and US Foods Jump on the 'Electric Semi Bandwagon' |url=https://ev-a2z.com/news/teslas-power-play-costco-sysco-and-us-foods-jump-on-the-electric-semi-bandwagon/ |url-status=live |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20240913160640/https://ev-a2z.com/news/teslas-power-play-costco-sysco-and-us-foods-jump-on-the-electric-semi-bandwagon/ |archive-date=September 13, 2024 |access-date=May 10, 2024 |work=EV-a2z |location=US}}</ref> In August 2024, third-party logistics provider NFI tested the Semi and reported an efficiency of {{cvt|1.64|kWh/mile|kWh/km}}.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Klender |first=Joey |date=August 20, 2024 |title=Tesla Semi's latest fleet customer details efficiency advantages |url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-semi-latest-fleet-customer-details-efficiency-advantages/}}</ref> In October 2024, [[DHL]] reported an efficiency of {{cvt|1.72|kWh/mile|kWh/km}} loaded with {{Convert|34000|kg|order=flip}} gross-combined weight over {{cvt|625|km|miles|order=flip|0}} on a single charge.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Lambert |first=Fred |date=October 14, 2024 |title=DHL tests Tesla Semi and confirms the electric truck's impressive performance |url=https://electrek.co/2024/10/14/dhl-tests-tesla-semi-and-confirms-the-electric-trucks-impressive-performance/ |access-date=October 18, 2024 |website=Electrek |language=en-US}}</ref>

On August 19, 2024, a Tesla Semi caught fire after a crash in [[Placer County, California|Placer County]], California, which closed [[Interstate 80|I-80]] for sixteen hours.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Sandra |first=McDonald |date=August 19, 2024 |title=Tesla big-rig battery ignites after crash, spewing fumes and shutting California freeway |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2024-08-19/tesla-semi-fire-toxic-fumes-highway |access-date=August 20, 2024 |website=Los Angeles Times |language=en-US |archive-date=September 13, 2024  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20240913160719/https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2024-08-19/tesla-semi-fire-toxic-fumes-highway |url-status=live }}</ref>

In May 2025, Tesla announced plans at ACT Expo to develop a [https://electrek.co/2025/04/30/tesla-semi-public-charging-network-coming-with-46-stations-in-2027/ public, 46-station Megacharger network] to support broader deployment of the Tesla Semi.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Lambert |first=Fred |date=2025-04-30 |title=Tesla Semi public charging network coming with 46 stations in 2027 |url=https://electrek.co/2025/04/30/tesla-semi-public-charging-network-coming-with-46-stations-in-2027/ |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20250723102140/https://electrek.co/2025/04/30/tesla-semi-public-charging-network-coming-with-46-stations-in-2027/ |archive-date=2025-07-23 |access-date=2026-06-02 |work=Electrek |language=en-US}}</ref>

On March 23, 2026, a new model of the Tesla Semi was shown with a sleeker front fascia and nearly {{cvt|1000|lb|kg}} less weight.<ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BCXSq1dmEB8 |title=Jay Leno Drives the 500-Mile Tesla Semi: The Death of Diesel? {{!}} Jay Leno's Garage |date=2026-03-23 |last=Jay Leno's Garage |access-date=2026-03-24 |via=YouTube}}</ref> On April 29, serial production was announced by Tesla.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web |last=John |first=Darryn |date=2026-04-29 |title=Tesla Semi finally reaches high-volume production after years of delays |url=https://driveteslacanada.ca/semi/tesla-semi-high-volume-production/ |access-date=2026-04-29 |website=Drive Tesla |language=en-US}}</ref>

== Design ==
[[File:Tesla Semi cockpit.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Cabin of a Semi prototype]]
Tesla Semi is powered by three carbon-fiber-wrapped motors; one operates continuously at optimal efficiency, while the other two motors provide additional power for acceleration and hills.<ref name=yahooNews20221205>{{Cite news |last1=Subramanian |first1=Pras |date=December 2, 2022 |title=Tesla Semi unveiled with tri-motor setup, megawatt charging tech |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/tesla-semi-unveiled-with-tri-motor-setup-megawatt-charging-tech-121619247.html |access-date=December 5, 2022 |publisher=Yahoo! Finance |language=en-US |archive-date=December 4, 2022  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20221204233255/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/tesla-semi-unveiled-with-tri-motor-setup-megawatt-charging-tech-121619247.html |url-status=live }}</ref> The stator and inverter are the same as in the [[Tesla Cybertruck|Cybertruck]].<ref name=":0" />

The driver's seat is centered inside the bullet-shaped cab. The ceiling allows an adult to stand. [[Touchscreen]] displays are set on both sides of the steering wheel, with no other instrument panels.<ref name="truckscom2017-11-17">{{cite web |last1=O'Dell |first1=John |date=November 17, 2017 |title=Elon Musk Unveils Superfast, 500-mile Range Tesla Electric Semi-Truck |url=https://www.trucks.com/2017/11/17/elon-musk-unveils-tesla-electric-semi-truck/ |access-date=November 17, 2017 |publisher=Trucks.com |quote=He provided no pricing information or specifics as to horsepower or torque figures. |archive-date=November 22, 2017  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171122142424/https://www.trucks.com/2017/11/17/elon-musk-unveils-tesla-electric-semi-truck/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The production model has side windows that completely retract.<ref name=":0" /><!-- For current "in production" design, will need more recent source. -->

It has a {{Cd|long=yes|link=car|0.4}}.<ref name=":0" />

The performance drop in cold weather is similar to diesel trucks (colder tires, etc.) Thermal management is active, routing heat to wherever it is needed (interior, battery).<ref name=":0" />

It includes the same camera set as Tesla's passenger vehicles. Tesla claims that its safety system can prevent jackknifing.<ref name="CarDriverBlog2017" />{{better source needed|date=December 2022}}<!-- For current "in production" design, will need more recent source. -->

The Tesla Semi has a 1.2-megawatt powertrain and charging system. It uses the same [[Lithium nickel manganese cobalt oxides|NMCA]] [[List of battery sizes#Lithium-ion batteries (rechargeable)|4680 cells]]<ref name="riz2026"/> found in the Cybertruck. The battery is rated to last {{cvt|1|E6miles|E6km}}. High-speed charging is supported at Tesla Megachargers. The battery is located near the ground to keep a low center of mass.<ref name=":0" />

The truck supports commercial semi tires. Downhill driving uses [[regenerative braking]], recharging the battery, without touching the brake pedal.<ref name=":0" />

The truck is able to power a refrigerated trailer or other high-powered machine without a [[Starter (engine)|pony motor]].<ref name=":0" />

The cab has two rear axles. One provides maximum torque: starting to drive, and driving uphill. The second one is for efficiency during cruising, avoiding a multi-speed transmission.<ref name=":0" />

It has a shorter wheelbase and a smaller battery.<ref name=":0" />

The infotainment system matches Tesla's other vehicles, and supports Bluetooth phone access.<ref name=":0" />

Compared to the initial version, the 2026 model offers:<ref name=":0" />

* {{cvt|1,000|lb|kg|adj=on}} weight reduction, in part by shifting to 48 volts
* 7% aerodynamic efficiency improvement
* Electric rather than hydraulic steering (not steer-by-wire)

== Costs ==
Semis cost under US$300,000, twice as much as a diesel truck, but $100,000 less than other battery-electric trucks.{{r | WSJ_2026-03-19 }} Because of a California $200,000 subsidy, California companies have placed over 1,000 Semi orders, which would double the number of battery-electric trucks serving the ports of [[Port of Long Beach|Long Beach]] and [[Port of Los Angeles|Los Angeles]].<ref name="WSJ_2026-03-19"> {{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/business/logistics/truckers-tesla-fans-semi-b0a66e6e | title=Tesla Finally Has Its First Semi-Truck and It’s Already a Hit With Truckers | last=Berger | first=Paul | newspaper=[[Wall Street Journal]] | date=2026-03-19 }} </ref> The company states that operating costs are 20% less than for comparable diesel trucks across the US, and 50% less in California.<ref name=":0" />

== Specifications ==
Semi comes in two trims, Long Range and Standard Range:<ref name=":1" /><ref name=":0" /><ref name="jay leno">{{Cite web |last=Levin |first=Tim |date=October 3, 2023 |title=Jay Leno towed 30 tons with a Tesla Semi and said it felt like nothing |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/tesla-semi-truck-jay-leno-drive-review-video-2023-10 |website=Business Insider |access-date=November 2, 2023  |archive-date=September 13, 2024  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20240913161207/https://www.businessinsider.com/tesla-semi-truck-jay-leno-drive-review-video-2023-10 |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Long Range ===
* Range: ~500 miles 
* 4680 cells 
* Electric steering assist
* Strengthened [[Tesla Cybertruck|Cybertruck]] actuators 
* 48 volt architecture (supports 12-volt accessories)
* Motors: 3 independent motors on rear axles 
* Power: up to 800 kW 
* Battery: 822 kWh<ref name="riz2026">{{cite web |last1=Akhtar |first1=Riz |title=Tesla Semi electric truck features massive 822 kWh battery pack and 800 km of range |url=https://thedriven.io/2026/05/09/tesla-semi-electric-truck-features-massive-822-kwh-battery-pack-and-800-km-of-range/ |website=The Driven |language=en-AU |date=9 May 2026}}</ref>
* Curb weight: 23,000 lbs 
* Energy consumption: 1.7 kWh/mi
* Charge speed: ~60% of range in 30 minutes
* Charge type: MCS 3.2 
* ePTO (electric [[power take off]]): ~25 kW

=== Standard Range (shorter version) ===
* Range: ~325 miles 
* Turning radius: similar to [[Tesla Model Y|Model Y]] 
* 4680 cells
* Electric steering assist
* Strengthened Cybertruck actuators 
* 48 volt architecture (supports 12-volt accessories)
* Motors: 3 independent motors on rear axles 
* Power: up to 800 kW 
* Battery: 548 kWh<ref name="riz2026"/>
* Curb weight: <20,000 lbs 
* Energy consumption: 1.7 kWh per mile 
* Charge speed: ~60% of range in 30 minutes 
* Charge type: MCS 3.2 
* ePTO: ~ 25 kW

== Prototype results ==
Prior to the 2026 production release:<ref name=":0" />

* The prototype fleet (a few hundred trucks) drove more than {{cvt|13.5|E6miles|E6km}}. 
* The busiest truck covered {{cvt|440,000|miles|km}}. 
* Fleet uptime was 95%. 
* 75-80% of Semi breakdowns were resolved and returned to the customer in less than 24 hours, with >50% returned within 30 minutes.

